<h2>Step 2 — Required elements</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>City + boundary identification.</strong> Name the city, the plate boundary type, and the specific plates involved. Example: "Tokyo sits on a convergent subduction zone where the Pacific Plate dives beneath the Okhotsk Plate."</li>
  <li><strong>Dominant hazards.</strong> List the 2–3 hazards your city faces given its boundary type, with one sentence on the mechanism for each. Don't just name them — say why that boundary type produces that hazard.</li>
  <li><strong>One historical analog.</strong> Choose one documented disaster from your city's region (or a comparable region with the same boundary type). Briefly describe what happened, when, and what was learned about engineering, warning systems, or human response.</li>
  <li><strong>Sources.</strong> Cite at least 2 reputable sources. Good ones: USGS Earthquake Hazards Program, Smithsonian Global Volcanism Program, IRIS, peer-reviewed journal articles, news of record (BBC, Reuters, NYT). Wikipedia is fine for navigation but not as a sole citation. Use any consistent citation format (MLA, APA, footnotes).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Format</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Written:</strong> PDF or Google Doc. Headings expected. No need for fancy layout. ≈500 words.</li>
  <li><strong>Video alternative:</strong> 60–90 second captioned video that covers the same four elements above.</li>
</ul>

